Rioting broke out in Toledo, Ohio as counter-protestors clashed with a neo-Nazi group, leading to chaos in the streets.
The police struggled to control the situation as violence escalated.
Mitt Romney condemned the supremacists, while arrests were made during the confrontation.
The incident highlighted racial tensions and the presence of hate groups in the area.
Mayor Jack Ford faced backlash for allowing the march, with threats and curses directed at him.
The community remained on edge, with concerns about potential violence during mass demonstrations.
Law enforcement and activists worked to prevent further confrontations and maintain peace.
